03746nam a22006135i 9780674029569DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740295697 a10.4159/97806740295692doi  a(DE-B1597)584806  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aB105.J87bC52 2006 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a172/.22221 aCi, Jiwei, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Two Faces of Justice /cJiwei Ci. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Elements of a Just Disposition -- t2 The Subjective Circumstances of Justice -- t3 The Objective Circumstances of Justice -- t4 The Idea of Voluntary Justice -- t5 The Moral Reach of Rational Egoism -- t6 Impartiality and Justification -- t7 A Progress of Reciprocity -- t8 Two Paths to Unconditional Justice -- t9 Forgetting and Resentment -- t10 Individual Forgiveness, Social Resentment -- t11 Justice and the Moralization of Sympathy -- t12 Justice as a Conscious Virtue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJustice is a human virtue that is at once unconditional and conditional. Under favorable circumstances, we can be motivated to act justly by the belief that we must live up to what justice requires, irrespective of whether we benefit from doing so. But our will to act justly is subject to conditions. We find it difficult to exercise the virtue of justice when others regularly fail to. Even if we appear to have overcome the difficulty, our reluctance often betrays itself in certain moral emotions. In this book, Jiwei Ci explores the dual nature of justice, in an attempt to make unitary sense of key features of justice reflected in its close relation to resentment, punishment, and forgiveness. Rather than pursue a search for normative principles, he probes the human psychology of justice to understand what motivates moral agents who seek to behave justly, and why their desire to be just is as precarious as it is uplifting., A wide-ranging treatment of enduring questions, The Two Faces of Justice can also be read as a remarkably discerning contribution to the Western discourse on justice re-launched in our time by John Rawls.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aJustice (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674029569zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674029569423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674029569/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK